{"title_page": "Igor Kolakovi\u0107", "text_new": "{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name             = Igor Kolakovi\u0107\n| image            = Igor Kolakovi\u0107 20190508 16.jpg\n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = {{flagicon|MNE}} [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1965|6|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Podgorica|Titograd]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]], [[Montenegro]]\n| position         = Setter\n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| spike            = \n| block            = \n| years            = 1979\u20131987<br> 1987\u20131991<br> 1991\u20131993<br> 1993\u20131994<br> 1994\u20131997\n| clubs            = {{flagicon|YUG}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]<br> {{flagicon|YUG}} [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]<br> {{flagicon|YUG}}{{flagicon|FRY}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]<br> {{flagicon|FRY}} [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]<br> {{flagicon|FRY}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n| nationalteam     = \n| nationalyears    = \n| currentcoachteam = \n| coachyears       = 1997\u20132009<br> 2003\u20132006<br> 2006\u20132014<br> 2010\u20132012<br> 2013\u20132016<br> 2017\u20132020\n| coachteams       = {{flagicon|MNE}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]<br> {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]] ({{Tooltip|AC|Assistant coach}})<br> {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]<br> {{flagicon|SLO}} [[ACH Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[AS Cannes Volley-Ball|AS Cannes]]<br> {{flagicon|IRN}} [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n}}\n\n'''Igor Kolakovi\u0107''' (born {{Birth date|1965|6|4|df=yes}}) is a former [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] [[volleyball]] player and coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/3319/ser-m-head-coach-of-european-champions-igor-kolakovic-is-looking-for-new-job.html |title=SER M: Head coach of European champions, Igor Kolakovic is looking for new job |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=23 April 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://odbojka.me/kolakovic-zelim-da-vodim-crnu-goru/ |title=Kolakovi\u0107: \u017delim da vodim Crnu Goru! |work=www.mnemagazin.me |language=cnr |date=15 December 2016 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIgor's wife, Sandra, is a former [[handball]] national team player, a former head coach of the [[Serbia women's national handball team]]. Igor received a bachelor degree of business administration in 1989 at the [[University of Montenegro Faculty of Economics]]. [[Aleksa Kolakovi\u0107]], son of Igor is a [[handball]] player.\n\n==Career==\n===As a player===\nKolakovic played as a setter for [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]] and [[Partizan|Partizan]] from 1979 to 1997, after which he became a head coach of the Podgorica team. He is two\u2013time [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Champion]] and two\u2013time Yugoslavian Cup winner.\n\n===As a coach===\nIgor Kolakovic replaced [[Ljubomir Travica]] as coach of the [[Serbia men's national volleyball team]] ahead of the [[2006 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2006 FIVB World Championship]], after assisting him for three years. He was the head coach of the Serbian national team from 2006 until 2014. He led Serbia to a gold medal at the [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2011 European Championship]] and bronze at the [[2007 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2007 European Championship]] and [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2013 European Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurovolley2011.com/en/news/38-news/572-serbian-fiesta-in-vienna-as-russia-misses-on-another-major-final-.html |title= Serbian fiesta in Vienna as Russia misses on another major final |work=www.eurovolley2011.com |date=17 September 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> In 2010 he achieved a great success at the [[2010 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2010 FIVB World Championship]] winning a bronze medal. He helped his team win two silver medals at the [[2008 FIVB World League]] and [[2009 FIVB World League]] and a bronze one at the [[2010 FIVB World League]]. In 2014 he resigned his post as as a coach of Serbia after eight years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/39453/breaking-kolakovic-resigns-as-head-coach-of-serbia.html |title=BREAKING: Kolakovi\u0107 resigns as head coach of Serbia! |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=15 September 2014 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> At club level, he won two titles of the [[Montenegrin Volleyball League|Montenegrin Champion]] in 2007 and 2008 with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]] and two titles of the [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Champion]] in 2011 and 2012 with [[ACH Volley]]. In 2017 he was appointed as a new head coach of the [[Iran men's national volleyball team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/80085/official-igor-kolakovic-takes-over-iran.html |title=OFFICIAL: Igor Kolakovic takes over Iran! |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=5 February 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/02/06/509332/Igor-Kolakovi-named-Iran-volleyball-coach-IRIVF-Davarzani-Tokyo-2020-Olympics-Japan |title=Igor Kolakovi\u0107 appointed Iran\u2019s volleyball team coach  |work=www.presstv.com |date=6 February 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/80097/.html |title=IRN M: Kolakovic \u2013\u201cBeing the coach of Iran will be a huge challenge\u201d |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=6 February 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> He led Iran to a bronze medal of the [[2017 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Grand Champions Cup|2017 FIVB World Grand Champions Cup]] defeating, among others, teams of [[United States men's national volleyball team|USA]], [[France men's national volleyball team|France]] and [[Italy men's national volleyball team|Italy]]. In 2019 Iran led by him won its 3rd [[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Asian Champion]] title.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tehrantimes.com/news/440381/Iran-volleyball-crowned-Asian-champions |title=Iran volleyball crowned Asian champions  |work=www.tehrantimes.com |date=21 September 2019 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> In 2020 he has been dismissed as a head coach of the [[Iran men's national volleyball team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/108679/irn-m-kolakovic-dismissed-iran-looking-for-new-head-coach.html |title=IRN M: Kolakovi\u0107 and Iran are parting ways |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Sporting achievements==\n===As a player===\n* '''[[CEV Challenge Cup]]'''\n** [[File:Simple silver cup.svg|16px]] 1989/1990 \u2013 with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''1988/1989''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Cup, with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1988/1989''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Championship]], with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1989/1990''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Cup, with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1989/1990''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Championship]], with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1990/1991''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Championship]], with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n\n===As a coach===\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''1997/1998''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2000/2001''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2001/2002''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2004/2005''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2004/2005''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2005/2006''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2005/2006''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2006/2007''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Montenegrin Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2006/2007''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Montenegrin Volleyball League|Montenegrin Championship]], with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2007/2008''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Montenegrin Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2007/2008''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Montenegrin Volleyball League|Montenegrin Championship]], with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2010/2011''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Slovenian Cup, with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2010/2011''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Championship]], with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Slovenian Cup, with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Championship]], with [[ACH Volley]]\n\n* '''National teams'''\n** '''2007''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2007 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2008''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2008 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2009''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2009 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2010''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2010 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2010''' [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2010 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|FIVB World Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2013''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2017''' [[File:Simple bronze cup.svg|16px]] [[2017 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Grand Champions Cup|FIVB World Grand Champions Cup]], with [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n** '''2018''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|Asian Games]], with [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n** '''2019''' [[File:Gold medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|AVC Asian Championship]], with [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.worldofvolley.com/wov-community/coaches/111586/igor-kolakovic.html worldofvolley.com coach profile]\n* [http://poland2014.fivb.org/en/competition/teams/srb-serbia 2014 FIVB World Championship \u2013 Team Serbia]\n* [http://worldleague.2017.fivb.com/en/group1/teams/iri-iran 2017 FIVB World League \u2013 Team Iran]\n* [http://www.eurohandball.com/ec/cl/women/2003-04/player/503911/SandraKolakovic eurohandball.com \u2013 Sandra Kolakovic]\n\n{{commons}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-sports}}\n{{succession box\n| before= {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Ra\u00fal Lozano (volleyball)|Ra\u00fal Lozano]]\n| after= TBD\n| title= Head coach of [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n| years= 2017\u20132020\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before= {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Ljubomir Travica]]\n| after= {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Nikola Grbi\u0107]]\n| title= Head coach of [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n| years= 2006\u20132014\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Iran national volleyball team managers}}\n{{Iran squad 2017 FIVB Men's World Grand Champions Cup}}\n{{Iran squad 2018 Asian Games Volleyball}}\n{{Iran squad 2018 FIVB Men's World Championship}}\n{{Serbia men's volleyball squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Serbia men's volleyball squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolakovi\u0107, Igor}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Podgorica]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:People from Podgorica]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:Volleyball coaches of international teams]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin expatriates in Serbia]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin expatriates in Slovenia]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin expatriates in France]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox volleyball biography\n| name             = Igor Kolakovi\u0107\n| image            = Igor Kolakovi\u0107 20190508 16.jpg\n| nickname         = \n| nationality      = {{flagicon|MNE}} [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]]\n| birth_date       = {{Birth date and age|1965|6|4|df=y}}\n| birth_place      = [[Podgorica|Titograd]], [[Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia|SFR Yugoslavia]], [[Montenegro]]\n| position         = Setter\n| height           = \n| weight           = \n| spike            = \n| block            = \n| years            = 1979\u20131987<br> 1987\u20131991<br> 1991\u20131993<br> 1993\u20131994<br> 1994\u20131997\n| clubs            = {{flagicon|YUG}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]<br> {{flagicon|YUG}} [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]<br> {{flagicon|YUG}}{{flagicon|FRY}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]<br> {{flagicon|FRY}} [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]<br> {{flagicon|FRY}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n| nationalteam     = \n| nationalyears    = \n| currentcoachteam = \n| coachyears       = 1997\u20132009<br> 2003\u20132006<br> 2006\u20132014<br> 2010\u20132012<br> 2013\u20132016<br> 2017\u20132020\n| coachteams       = {{flagicon|MNE}} [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]<br> {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]] ({{Tooltip|AC|Assistant coach}})<br> {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]<br> {{flagicon|SLO}} [[ACH Volley]]<br> {{flagicon|FRA}} [[AS Cannes Volley-Ball|AS Cannes]]<br> {{flagicon|IRN}} [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n}}\n\n'''Igor Kolakovi\u0107''' (born {{Birth date|1965|6|4|df=yes}}) is a former [[Montenegro|Montenegrin]] [[volleyball]] player and coach.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/3319/ser-m-head-coach-of-european-champions-igor-kolakovic-is-looking-for-new-job.html |title=SER M: Head coach of European champions, Igor Kolakovic is looking for new job |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=23 April 2012 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://odbojka.me/kolakovic-zelim-da-vodim-crnu-goru/ |title=Kolakovi\u0107: \u017delim da vodim Crnu Goru! |work=www.mnemagazin.me |language=cnr |date=15 December 2016 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIgor's wife, Sandra, is a former [[handball]] national team player, a former head coach of the [[Serbia women's national handball team]]. Igor received a bachelor degree of business administration in 1989 at the [[University of Montenegro Faculty of Economics]]. [[Aleksa Kolakovi\u0107]], son of Igor is a [[handball]] player.\n\n==Career==\n===As a player===\nKolakovic played as a setter for [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]] and [[Partizan|Partizan]] from 1979 to 1997, after which he became a head coach of the Podgorica team. He is two\u2013time [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Champion]] and two\u2013time Yugoslavian Cup winner.\n\n===As a coach===\nIgor Kolakovic replaced [[Ljubomir Travica]] as coach of the [[Serbia men's national volleyball team]] ahead of the [[2006 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2006 FIVB World Championship]], after assisting him for three years. He was the head coach of the Serbian national team from 2006 until 2014. He led Serbia to a gold medal at the [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2011 European Championship]] and bronze at the [[2007 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2007 European Championship]] and [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|2013 European Championship]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.eurovolley2011.com/en/news/38-news/572-serbian-fiesta-in-vienna-as-russia-misses-on-another-major-final-.html |title= Serbian fiesta in Vienna as Russia misses on another major final |work=www.eurovolley2011.com |date=17 September 2011 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> In 2010 he achieved a great success at the [[2010 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|2010 FIVB World Championship]] winning a bronze medal. He helped his team win two silver medals at the [[2008 FIVB World League]] and [[2009 FIVB World League]] and a bronze one at the [[2010 FIVB World League]]. In 2014 he resigned his post as as a coach of Serbia after eight years.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/39453/breaking-kolakovic-resigns-as-head-coach-of-serbia.html |title=BREAKING: Kolakovi\u0107 resigns as head coach of Serbia! |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=15 September 2014 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> At club level, he won two titles of the [[Montenegrin Volleyball League|Montenegrin Champion]] in 2007 and 2008 with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]] and two titles of the [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Champion]] in 2011 and 2012 with [[ACH Volley]]. In 2017 he was appointed as a new head coach of the [[Iran men's national volleyball team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/80085/official-igor-kolakovic-takes-over-iran.html |title=OFFICIAL: Igor Kolakovic takes over Iran! |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=5 February 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.presstv.com/Detail/2017/02/06/509332/Igor-Kolakovi-named-Iran-volleyball-coach-IRIVF-Davarzani-Tokyo-2020-Olympics-Japan |title=Igor Kolakovi\u0107 appointed Iran\u2019s volleyball team coach  |work=www.presstv.com |date=6 February 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/80097/.html |title=IRN M: Kolakovic \u2013\u201cBeing the coach of Iran will be a huge challenge\u201d |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=6 February 2017 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> He led Iran to a bronze medal of the [[2017 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Grand Champions Cup|2017 FIVB World Grand Champions Cup]] defeating, among others, teams of [[United States men's national volleyball team|USA]], [[France men's national volleyball team|France]] and [[Italy men's national volleyball team|Italy]]. In 2019 Iran led by him won its 3rd [[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|Asian Champion]] title.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.tehrantimes.com/news/440381/Iran-volleyball-crowned-Asian-champions |title=Iran volleyball crowned Asian champions  |work=www.tehrantimes.com |date=21 September 2019 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> In 2020 he has been dismissed as a head coach of the [[Iran men's national volleyball team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.worldofvolley.com/Latest_news/Othercountries/108679/irn-m-kolakovic-dismissed-iran-looking-for-new-head-coach.html |title=IRN M: Kolakovi\u0107 and Iran are parting ways |work=www.worldofvolley.com |date=28 March 2020 |accessdate=19 April 2020}}</ref> \n\n==Sporting achievements==\n===As a player===\n* '''[[CEV Challenge Cup]]'''\n** [[File:Simple silver cup.svg|16px]] 1989/1990 \u2013 with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''1988/1989''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Cup, with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1988/1989''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Championship]], with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1989/1990''' [[File:Simple gold cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Cup, with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1989/1990''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Championship]], with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n** '''1990/1991''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Yugoslav Volleyball Championship|Yugoslavian Championship]], with [[OK Partizan|Partizan]]\n\n===As a coach===\n* '''National championships'''\n** '''1997/1998''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2000/2001''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2001/2002''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Yugoslavian Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2004/2005''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2004/2005''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2005/2006''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2005/2006''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Serbia and Montenegro Championship, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2006/2007''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Montenegrin Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2006/2007''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Montenegrin Volleyball League|Montenegrin Championship]], with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2007/2008''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Montenegrin Cup, with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2007/2008''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Montenegrin Volleyball League|Montenegrin Championship]], with [[OK Budu\u0107nost Podgorica|Budu\u0107nost Podgorica]]\n** '''2010/2011''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Slovenian Cup, with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2010/2011''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Championship]], with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] Slovenian Cup, with [[ACH Volley]]\n** '''2011/2012''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Slovenian Volleyball League|Slovenian Championship]], with [[ACH Volley]]\n\n* '''National teams'''\n** '''2007''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2007 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2008''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2008 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2009''' [[File:Silver medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2009 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2010''' [[File:Bronze medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[2010 FIVB Volleyball World League|FIVB World League]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2010''' [[File:Bronze medal world centered-2.svg|16px]] [[2010 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Championship|FIVB World Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2011''' [[File:Gold medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2011 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2013''' [[File:Bronze medal europe.svg|16px]] [[2013 Men's European Volleyball Championship|CEV European Championship]], with [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n** '''2017''' [[File:Simple bronze cup.svg|16px]] [[2017 FIVB Volleyball Men's World Grand Champions Cup|FIVB World Grand Champions Cup]], with [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n** '''2018''' [[File:Gold medal with cup.svg|16px]] [[Volleyball at the 2018 Asian Games \u2013 Men's tournament|Asian Games]], with [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n** '''2019''' [[File:Gold medal asia.svg|16px]] [[2019 Asian Men's Volleyball Championship|AVC Asian Championship]], with [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.worldofvolley.com/wov-community/coaches/111586/igor-kolakovic.html worldofvolley.com coach profile]\n* [http://poland2014.fivb.org/en/competition/teams/srb-serbia 2014 FIVB World Championship \u2013 Team Serbia]\n* [http://worldleague.2017.fivb.com/en/group1/teams/iri-iran 2017 FIVB World League \u2013 Team Iran]\n* [http://www.eurohandball.com/ec/cl/women/2003-04/player/503911/SandraKolakovic eurohandball.com \u2013 Sandra Kolakovic]\n\n{{commons}}\n{{s-start}}\n{{S-sports}}\n{{succession box\n| before= {{flagicon|ARG}} [[Ra\u00fal Lozano (volleyball)|Ra\u00fal Lozano]]\n| after= TBD\n| title= Head coach of [[Iran men's national volleyball team|Iran]]\n| years= 2017\u20132020\n}}\n{{succession box\n| before= {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Ljubomir Travica]]\n| after= {{flagicon|SRB}} [[Nikola Grbi\u0107]]\n| title= Head coach of [[Serbia men's national volleyball team|Serbia]]\n| years= 2006\u20132014\n}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Iran national volleyball team managers}}\n{{Iran squad 2017 FIVB Men's World Grand Champions Cup}}\n{{Iran squad 2018 Asian Games Volleyball}}\n{{Iran squad 2018 FIVB Men's World Championship}}\n{{Serbia men's volleyball squad 2008 Summer Olympics}}\n{{Serbia men's volleyball squad 2012 Summer Olympics}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kolakovic, Igor}}\n[[Category:1965 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Serbian volleyball coaches]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Podgorica]]\n[[Category:Yugoslav men's volleyball players]]\n[[Category:People from Podgorica]]\n[[Category:Montenegrin men's volleyball players]]\n", "name_user": "Maister1921", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Igor_Kolakovi%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "North Shore Albions", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby league club\n| clubname           = North Shore Albions\n| image              = \n| emblem             = \n| fullname           = North Shore Albions Rugby League Football Club\n| nickname           =\n| short name         = \n| web                = \n| colours            = Black and White\n| founded            = 1909<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Northern Union Game/Auckland Rugby Football League\n| page =7\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = XLVI\n| number = 14117\n| date = 1920-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090720.2.99.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n| exited             = 2005\n| ground             = Bayswater Park\n| ground2            = [[Devonport Domain]]\n| ground3            = \n| ceo                = \n| coach              = \n| manager            = \n| captain            = \n| league             = [[Auckland Rugby League]]\n| premierships       = 1913, 1914, 1928, 1932, 1933, 1941\n| minorpremierships  = 1940, 1941, 1946, 1955,\n| runnerups          = \n| cup1     = Stormont Shield\n| cup1titles = 1930, 1931, 1933, 1940, 1945, 1954, \n| cup2 = Roope Rooster\n| cup2titles = 1915, 1931, 1945, 1954\n| cup3 = Norton Cup\n| cup3titles = 1931, 1973, 1990, 1991\n}}\n\nThe '''North Shore Albions''' were a [[rugby league]] club based on the North Shore of [[Auckland]] in [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]] before moving to Bayswater at a later time.  They began in 1909 and folded in the early 2000s due to a lack of playing numbers. At the start of the 1920 season they were renamed '''Devonport United''' when they amalgamated with the Sunnyside club.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = LVII\n| number = 17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> It was proposed at the merger that they be known as North Shore Albions but Sunnyside objected and the name of Devonport United was chosen. In 1937, 17 years later at their annual general meeting they decided to revert back to the name \"North Shore Albions\" as they had been commonly referred to as \"shore\" for many years.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport United/North Shore Albions\n| page =23\n| work= [[Auckland Star]]\n| volume = LXVIII\n| number = 65\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19370318.2.185.2\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2020-03-25}}</ref> Chairman H Mann made the proposal and it was adopted by the club. Aside from Northcote they were the only club on the North Shore at that time. They closed their doors in 2005.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Acquisitions\n| page =2\n| work = Devonport Historical and Museum Society Newsletter\n| volume = 6\n| number = 2\n| date = 2005-10-01\n| url =http://www.devonportmuseum.org.nz/dmuseum2/assets/Uploads/Newsletter/october2005.pdf\n| accessdate = 2019-11-13}}</ref> The only remaining club connected to them are the Northern Brothers who are based at Ngataringa Bay Sports Field. Their senior team is an amalgamation of East Coast Bays Barracudas and Glenfield Greyhounds but are based more in the North Shore Albions traditional area which includes the navy ground which has provided many players and teams over the years. The predominant colours are black and green which have been common colours of all the North Shore clubs over the decades.\n\n==History==\nThey were formed in 1909 when the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition was in its infancy, having its own first General Meeting that same season.\n\nThey were officially born on the evening of 23 July 1909 when a meeting was held at the Devonport Council Chambers. The following people were elected officers for the inaugural season: President \u2013 Dr. Guinness, Vice Presidents \u2013 Dr. Bennett, Captain Pilkington, Mr W. Swinnerton, Mr. A. Goldwater, and Mr. D. W. McLean, Committee \u2013 Mr. F. Gladding, Mr. P. Gerrard, Mr. Clark, Mr. Marshall, Mr. Wells, and Mr. Powell, with Mr. A. J. Powley the Secretary and Treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northern Union Football\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]\n| volume = XL\n| number = 174\n| date = 23 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090723.2.25/NZH19090726.2.90.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThey played in the first ever rugby league match between two Auckland club teams when they played [[City Rovers]] at Eagleton's Paddock in [[Epsom, New Zealand|Epsom]]. North Shore put out a strong side and won the match by 44 points to 22.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northern Union Game/First League Match/Some Heavy Scoring\n| page = 7\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = XLVI\n| number = 14122\n| date = 26 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090726.2.90.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> Their team was made up of the following players: F. Neighbour, F. Gladding, [[Richard Wynyard]], Gerrard, [[George Seagar]], [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]], Griffin, B. Wells, Allen, C. Wells, Percival, Shaw, McReynolds, Marshall, Powell, [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]], McDonald, and Stevens.\n\nThey also played one match on the Devonport Domain that year against a combined town team which they won by 26 points to 10.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Northern Union Game/North Shore V Combined Town\n| page = 7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = XLVI\n| number = 14140\n| date = 16 August 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090816.2.97.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Titles==\nThey were particularly successful in their early years. They won the senior grade 6 times from 1913<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The 'Knockout' Competition/Champions Beaten by Newton/City Defeat Ponsonby\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = L\n| number = 15335\n| date = 1913-06-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19130623.2.134.2\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2019-08-12}}</ref> to 1941, while they won the minor premiership (Rukutai Shield) 4 times from 1940 to 1955. As Auckland grew and the North Shore gentrified North Shore struggled to remain the power house it once was and it dropped down the grades. Its last notable title was the Norton Cup which they won in 1990 and 1991.\n\n==Notable players==\n* [[Dennis Hale (rugby league)|Dennis Hale]]\n* [[Karl Ifwersen]]\n* [[Alfred Jackson (rugby league)|Alfred Jackson]]\n* [[Bert Laing]]\n* [[Verdun Scott]]\n* [[George Seagar]]\n* [[Ivor Stirling]]\n* [[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]\n* [[Stan Weston]]\n* [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]]\n* [[Richard Wynyard]]\n* [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league clubs]]\n[[Category:Rugby clubs established in 1909]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2005]]\n[[Category:1909 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2005 disestablishments in New Zealand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox rugby league club\n| clubname           = North Shore Albions\n| image              = \n| emblem             = \n| fullname           = North Shore Albions Rugby League Football Club\n| nickname           =\n| short name         = \n| web                = \n| colours            = Black and White\n| founded            = 1909<ref>{{cite news\n| title =The Northern Union Game/Auckland Rugby Football League\n| page =7\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = XLVI\n| number = 14117\n| date = 1920-07-20\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090720.2.99.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2019-11-13}}</ref>\n\n| exited             = 2005\n| ground             = Bayswater Park\n| ground2            = [[Devonport Domain]]\n| ground3            = \n| ceo                = \n| coach              = \n| manager            = \n| captain            = \n| league             = [[Auckland Rugby League]]\n| premierships       = 1913, 1914, 1928, 1932, 1933, 1941\n| minorpremierships  = 1940, 1941, 1946, 1955,\n| runnerups          = \n| cup1     = Stormont Shield\n| cup1titles = 1930, 1931, 1933, 1940, 1945, 1954, \n| cup2 = Roope Rooster\n| cup2titles = 1915, 1931, 1945, 1954\n| cup3 = Norton Cup\n| cup3titles = 1931, 1973, 1990, 1991\n}}\n\nThe '''North Shore Albions''' were a [[rugby league]] club based on the North Shore of [[Auckland]] in [[Devonport, New Zealand|Devonport]] before moving to Bayswater at a later time.  They began in 1909 and folded in the early 2000s due to a lack of playing numbers. At the start of the 1920 season they were renamed '''Devonport United''' when they amalgamated with the Sunnyside club.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Two Clubs Amalgamate\n| page =6\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = LVII\n| number = 17436\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19200405.2.100\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2019-08-10}}</ref> It was proposed at the merger that they be known as North Shore Albions but Sunnyside objected and the name of Devonport United was chosen. In 1937, 17 years later at their annual general meeting they decided to revert back to the name \"North Shore Albions\" as they had been commonly referred to as \"shore\" for many years.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Devonport United/North Shore Albions\n| page =23\n| work= [[Auckland Star]]\n| volume = LXVIII\n| number = 65\n| date = 1920-03-05\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19370318.2.185.2\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2020-03-25}}</ref> Chairman H Mann made the proposal and it was adopted by the club. Aside from Northcote they were the only club on the North Shore at that time. They closed their doors in 2005.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =New Acquisitions\n| page =2\n| work = Devonport Historical and Museum Society Newsletter\n| volume = 6\n| number = 2\n| date = 2005-10-01\n| url =http://www.devonportmuseum.org.nz/dmuseum2/assets/Uploads/Newsletter/october2005.pdf\n| accessdate = 2019-11-13}}</ref> The only remaining club connected to them are the Northern Brothers who are based at Ngataringa Bay Sports Field. Their senior team is an amalgamation of East Coast Bays Barracudas and Glenfield Greyhounds but are based more in the North Shore Albions traditional area which includes the navy ground which has provided many players and teams over the years. The predominant colours are black and green which have been common colours of all the North Shore clubs over the decades.\n\n==History==\nThey were formed in 1909 when the [[Auckland Rugby League]] competition was in its infancy, having its own first General Meeting that same season.\n\nThey were officially born on the evening of 23 July 1909 when a meeting was held at the Devonport Council Chambers. The following people were elected officers for the inaugural season: President - Dr. Guinness, Vice Presidents - Dr. Bennett, Captain Pilkington, Mr W. Swinnerton, Mr. A. Goldwater, and Mr. D. W. McLean, Committee - Mr. F. Gladding, Mr. P. Gerrard, Mr. Clark, Mr. Marshall, Mr. Wells, and Mr. Powell, with Mr. A. J. Powley the Secretary and Treasurer.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northern Union Football\n| page = 3\n| work=[[Auckland Star]]\n| volume = XL\n| number = 174\n| date = 23 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/AS19090723.2.25/NZH19090726.2.90.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 13 November 2019}}</ref>\n\nThey played in the first ever rugby league match between two Auckland club teams when they played [[City Rovers]] at Eagleton's Paddock in [[Epsom, New Zealand|Epsom]]. North Shore put out a strong side and won the match by 44 points to 22.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =Northern Union Game/First League Match/Some Heavy Scoring\n| page = 7\n| work= [[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = XLVI\n| number = 14122\n| date = 26 July 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090726.2.90.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref> Their team was made up of the following players: F. Neighbour, F. Gladding, [[Richard Wynyard]], Gerrard, [[George Seagar]], [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]], Griffin, B. Wells, Allen, C. Wells, Percival, Shaw, McReynolds, Marshall, Powell, [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]], McDonald, and Stevens.\n\nThey also played one match on the Devonport Domain that year against a combined town team which they won by 26 points to 10.<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The Northern Union Game/North Shore V Combined Town\n| page = 7\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = XLVI\n| number = 14140\n| date = 16 August 1909\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19090816.2.97.1\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 1 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Titles==\nThey were particularly successful in their early years. They won the senior grade 6 times from 1913<ref>{{cite news \n| title =The 'Knockout' Competition/Champions Beaten by Newton/City Defeat Ponsonby\n| page =9\n| work=[[The New Zealand Herald]]\n| volume = L\n| number = 15335\n| date = 1913-06-23\n| url =https://paperspast.natlib.govt.nz/newspapers/NZH19130623.2.134.2\n| via = National Library of New Zealand\n| accessdate = 2019-08-12}}</ref> to 1941, while they won the minor premiership (Rukutai Shield) 4 times from 1940 to 1955. As Auckland grew and the North Shore gentrified North Shore struggled to remain the power house it once was and it dropped down the grades. Its last notable title was the Norton Cup which they won in 1990 and 1991.\n\n==Notable players==\n* [[Dennis Hale (rugby league)|Dennis Hale]]\n* [[Karl Ifwersen]]\n* [[Alfred Jackson (rugby league)|Alfred Jackson]]\n* [[Bert Laing]]\n* [[Verdun Scott]]\n* [[George Seagar]]\n* [[Ivor Stirling]]\n* [[Stan Walters (rugby league)|Stan Walters]]\n* [[Stan Weston]]\n* [[Frank Woodward (rugby league)|Frank Woodward]]\n* [[Richard Wynyard]]\n* [[William Wynyard (rugby league)|William Wynyard]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Auckland rugby league clubs]]\n[[Category:Rugby clubs established in 1909]]\n[[Category:Sports clubs disestablished in 2005]]\n[[Category:1909 establishments in New Zealand]]\n[[Category:2005 disestablishments in New Zealand]]\n", "name_user": "Schwede66", "label": "safe", "comment": "fixeddashesusing ascript", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/North_Shore_Albions"}
{"title_page": "The Man Who Could Work Miracles (story)", "text_new": "{{Infobox short story <!--See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]]-->\n| name              = The Man Who Could Work Miracles\n| image             = The Man Who Could Work Miracles by Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Forestier 05.png\n| caption           = \n| author            = [[H. G. Wells]]\n| country           = United Kingdom\n| genre             = [[Science fiction]]\n| published_in      = \n| publication_type  = \n| publisher         = \n| media_type        = \n| pub_date          = \n}}\n\"'''The Man Who Could Work Miracles'''\" is a British [[fantasy]]\u2013[[comedy]] [[short story]] by [[H. G. Wells]] first published in 1898 in ''[[The Illustrated London News]]''. It carried the subtitle \"A Pantoum in Prose.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3pxbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT811&lpg=PT811&dq=The+Man+Who+Could+Work+Miracles+1898+in+The+Illustrated+London+News&source=bl&ots=2DCsSrPchM&sig=dGXtKKSuJFyCaVmEa0SSeBxeSXo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-8ZGT35jYAhXlLcAKHYZED5g4ChDoAQgrMAE#v=onepage&q=The+Man+Who+Could+Work+Miracles+1898+in+The+Illustrated+London+News&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of the British Short Story|first=Andrew|last=Maunder|date=22 April 2015|publisher=Infobase Learning|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe story is an early example of [[contemporary fantasy]] (not yet recognized, at the time, as a specific sub-genre). In common with later works falling within this definition, the story places a major fantasy premise (a wizard with enormous, virtually unlimited magic power) not in an exotic semi-medieval setting but in the drab routine daily life of suburban London, very familiar to Wells himself.\n\n==Plot summary==\nIn an English [[public house]], George McWhirter Fotheringay vigorously asserts the impossibility of [[miracle]]s during an argument. By way of demonstration, Fotheringay commands an [[oil lamp]] to flame upside down and it does so, to his own astonishment. His acquaintances think it a trick and quickly dismiss it.\n\nFotheringay explores his new power. After magically accomplishing his daily chores as an office clerk, Fotheringay quits early to a park to practice further. He encounters a local [[Constable#United Kingdom and the Commonwealth|constable]], who is accidentally injured. In the ensuing altercation, Fotheringay unintentionally sends the policeman to [[Hades]]; hours later, Fotheringay relocates him safely to [[San Francisco]].\n\nUnnerved by these miracles, Fotheringay attends local Sunday church services. The clergyman, Mr. Maydig, preaches about unnatural occurrences. Fotheringay is deeply moved, and meets Maydig in his manse for advice. After a few petty demonstrations, the minister becomes enthusiastic and suggests that Fotheringay should use these abilities to benefit others. That night they walk the town streets, healing illness and vice and improving public works.\n\nMaydig plans to reform the whole world. He suggests that they could disregard their obligations for the next day if Fotheringay could stop the night altogether. Fotheringay agrees and stops the motion of the Earth. His clumsy wording of the wish causes all objects on Earth to be hurled from the surface with great force. Pandemonium ensues, but Fotheringay miraculously ensures his own safety back on the ground. In fact (though he is not aware of the enormity of what he had done) the whole of humanity except for himself had perished in a single instant.\n\nFotheringay is unable to return the Earth to its prior state. He repents, and wishes that the power be taken from him and the world restored to a time before he had the power. Fotheringay immediately finds himself back in the public house, discussing miracles with his friends as before, without any recollection of previous events.\n\nThe all-knowing narrator thus tells the reader that he or she had died \"a year ago\" (the story was published in 1897) and was then resurrected - but has no recollection of anything special having happened.\n\n==Film, TV or theatrical adaptations==\nIn [[1936 in film|1936]], the story was adapted to [[The Man Who Could Work Miracles|a film]] starring [[Roland Young]] as Fotheringay. Wells co-wrote the screenplay with [[Lajos B\u00edr\u00f3]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/472462/credits.html|title=BFI Screenonline: Man Who Could Work Miracles, The (1937) Credits|website=www.screenonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIt was first adapted for [[BBC Radio]] in 1934 by [[Laurence Gilliam]] and broadcast on 4 June that year.<ref>[[Radio Times]], Issue 557, 4 June 1934[http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/regional/london/1934-06-04]</ref> It continued to be adapted multiple times for [[BBC Radio]] including 1956 by [[Dennis Main Wilson]] and broadcast on New Year's Day. It starred [[Tony Hancock]] as Fotheringay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/00b5e2f2610d4bcd81a728d8bcec747a|title=The Man Who Could Work Miracles|date=28 December 1956|publisher=|issue=1729|pages=18|via=BBC Genome}}</ref>\n\nThe story idea was used as the basis for director [[Terry Jones]]'s 2015 film ''[[Absolutely Anything]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Plumb|first1=Ali|title=Terry Jones On His New Sci-Fi Comedy ''Absolutely Anything''|url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1858|accessdate=15 August 2015|work=Empire Magazine|publisher=Bauer Consumer Media}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of the world stopping rotating was taken up in 1972 by [[Lester del Rey]], who suggested to three SF writers to write stories based on the assumption that God does it in order to unequivocally prove His existence to all humanity. The three resulting stories were published together under the name \"The Day the Earth Stood Still\", comprising \"A Chapter of Revelation\" by [[Poul Anderson]], \"Things Which Are Caesar's\" by [[Gordon R. Dickson]] and \"Thomas the Proclaimer\" by [[Robert Silverberg]]. The three stories share the assumption that \u2013 the miracle in this case issuing directly from God in person, rather than from Wells' fumbling human protagonist \u2013 care was taken to prevent the disastrous results evident in the original Wells story. The dramatic radio broadcast appearing in the beginning of Silverberg's version indicates that, when writing, he was familiar with the Wells story: ''\"Latest observatory reports confirm that no appreciable momentum effects could be detected as Earth shifted to its present period of rotation. Scientists agree that the world's abrupt slowing on its axis should have produced a global catastrophe leading, perhaps, to the destruction of all life. However, nothing but minor tidal disturbances have been observed so far\"''.<ref>[[Robert Silverberg]], \"Thomas the Proclaimer\", Ch.1</ref>\n\nFor his part, the Portuguese [[Jos\u00e9 Saramago]] apparently refers to the Wells story in his novel ''[[Cain (novel)| Cain]]'', an irreverent retelling of the [[Bible]], when retelling the episode of God \"stopping the sun\" in the [[Book of Joshua]] (to which the pastor in the Wells story also refers). The very flawed God depicted by Saramago was unable to stop the disastrous effects of stopping the movement of the Easth \u2013 so he did not do so, performing just a much simpler and limited miracle which still did the job.\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Man Who Could Work Miracles|The Man Who Could Work Miracles}}\n* \"[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/27365/27365-h/27365-h.htm#Page_325 The Man Who Could Work Miracles]\" at [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* [http://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/w/wells/hg/w45cb/chapter21.html ''The Man Who Could Work Miracles'':] short story by H. G. Wells\n* {{librivox book | title=The Man who could Work Miracles | author=H. G. Wells}}\n* {{Isfdb title|id=54718|title=The Man Who Could Work Miracles}}\n* {{IMDb title|id=0029201}}\n\n{{Clear}}\n{{H. G. Wells}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Man Who Could Work Miracles, The}}\n[[Category:1898 short stories]]\n[[Category:Comic short stories]]\n[[Category:Fantasy short stories]]\n[[Category:Short stories by H. G. Wells]]\n[[Category:Works originally published in The Illustrated London News]]\n[[Category:Short stories adapted into films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox short story <!--See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Novels]]-->\n| name              = The Man Who Could Work Miracles\n| image             = The Man Who Could Work Miracles by Am\u00e9d\u00e9e Forestier 05.png\n| caption           = \n| author            = [[H. G. Wells]]\n| country           = United Kingdom\n| genre             = [[Science fiction]]\n| published_in      = \n| publication_type  = \n| publisher         = \n| media_type        = \n| pub_date          = \n}}\n\"'''The Man Who Could Work Miracles'''\" is a British [[fantasy]]\u2013[[comedy]] [[short story]] by [[H. G. Wells]] first published in 1898 in ''[[The Illustrated London News]]''. It carried the subtitle \"A Pantoum in Prose.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=3pxbAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT811&lpg=PT811&dq=The+Man+Who+Could+Work+Miracles+1898+in+The+Illustrated+London+News&source=bl&ots=2DCsSrPchM&sig=dGXtKKSuJFyCaVmEa0SSeBxeSXo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwj-8ZGT35jYAhXlLcAKHYZED5g4ChDoAQgrMAE#v=onepage&q=The+Man+Who+Could+Work+Miracles+1898+in+The+Illustrated+London+News&f=false|title=Encyclopedia of the British Short Story|first=Andrew|last=Maunder|date=22 April 2015|publisher=Infobase Learning|via=Google Books}}</ref>\n\nThe story is an early example of [[contemporary fantasy]] (not yet recognized, at the time, as a specific sub-genre). In common with later works falling within this definition, the story places a major fantasy premise (a wizard with enormous, virtually unlimited magic power) not in an exotic semi-medieval setting but in the drab routine daily life of suburban London, very familiar to Wells himself.\n\n==Plot summary==\nIn an English [[public house]], George McWhirter Fotheringay vigorously asserts the impossibility of [[miracle]]s during an argument. By way of demonstration, Fotheringay commands an [[oil lamp]] to flame upside down and it does so, to his own astonishment. His acquaintances think it a trick and quickly dismiss it.\n\nFotheringay explores his new power. After magically accomplishing his daily chores as an office clerk, Fotheringay quits early to a park to practice further. He encounters a local [[Constable#United Kingdom and the Commonwealth|constable]], who is accidentally injured. In the ensuing altercation, Fotheringay unintentionally sends the policeman to [[Hades]]; hours later, Fotheringay relocates him safely to [[San Francisco]].\n\nUnnerved by these miracles, Fotheringay attends local Sunday church services. The clergyman, Mr. Maydig, preaches about unnatural occurrences. Fotheringay is deeply moved, and meets Maydig in his manse for advice. After a few petty demonstrations, the minister becomes enthusiastic and suggests that Fotheringay should use these abilities to benefit others. That night they walk the town streets, healing illness and vice and improving public works.\n\nMaydig plans to reform the whole world. He suggests that they could disregard their obligations for the next day if Fotheringay could stop the night altogether. Fotheringay agrees and stops the motion of the Earth. His clumsy wording of the wish causes all objects on Earth to be hurled from the surface with great force. Pandemonium ensues, but Fotheringay miraculously ensures his own safety back on the ground. In fact (though he is not aware of the enormity of what he had done) the whole of humanity except for himself had perished in a single instant.\n\nFotheringay is unable to return the Earth to its prior state. He repents, and wishes that the power be taken from him and the world restored to a time before he had the power. Fotheringay immediately finds himself back in the public house, discussing miracles with his friends as before, without any recollection of previous events.\n\nThe all-knowing narrator thus tells the reader that he or she had died \"a year ago\" (the story was published in 1897) and was then resurrected - but has no recollection of anything special having happened.\n\n==Film, TV or theatrical adaptations==\nIn [[1936 in film|1936]], the story was adapted to [[The Man Who Could Work Miracles|a film]] starring [[Roland Young]] as Fotheringay. Wells co-wrote the screenplay with [[Lajos B\u00edr\u00f3]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.screenonline.org.uk/film/id/472462/credits.html|title=BFI Screenonline: Man Who Could Work Miracles, The (1937) Credits|website=www.screenonline.org.uk}}</ref>\n\nIt was first adapted for [[BBC Radio]] in 1934 by [[Laurence Gilliam]] and broadcast on 4 June that year.<ref>[[Radio Times]], Issue 557, 4 June 1934[http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/schedules/regional/london/1934-06-04]</ref> It continued to be adapted multiple times for [[BBC Radio]] including 1956 by [[Dennis Main Wilson]] and broadcast on New Year's Day. It starred [[Tony Hancock]] as Fotheringay.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://genome.ch.bbc.co.uk/00b5e2f2610d4bcd81a728d8bcec747a|title=The Man Who Could Work Miracles|date=28 December 1956|publisher=|issue=1729|pages=18|via=BBC Genome}}</ref>\n\nThe story idea was used as the basis for director [[Terry Jones]]'s 2015 film ''[[Absolutely Anything]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Plumb|first1=Ali|title=Terry Jones On His New Sci-Fi Comedy ''Absolutely Anything''|url=http://www.empireonline.com/interviews/interview.asp?IID=1858|accessdate=15 August 2015|work=Empire Magazine|publisher=Bauer Consumer Media}}</ref>\n\nThe idea of the world stopping rotating was taken up in 1972 by [[Lester del Rey]], who suggested to three SF writers to write stories based on the assumption that God does it in order to unequivocally prove His existence to all humanity. The three resulting stories were published together under the name \"The Day the Earth Stood Still\", comprising \"A Chapter of Revelation\" by [[Poul Anderson]], \"Things Which Are Caesar's\" by [[Gordon R. Dickson]] and \"Thomas the Proclaimer\" by [[Robert Silverberg]]. The three stories share the assumption that \u2013 the miracle in this case issuing directly from God in person, rather than from Wells' fumbling human protagonist \u2013 care was taken to prevent the disastrous results evident in the original Wells story. The dramatic radio broadcast appearing in the beginning of Silverberg's version indicates that, when writing, he was familiar with the Wells story: ''\"Latest observatory reports confirm that no appreciable momentum effects could be detected as Earth shifted to its present period of rotation. Scientists agree that the world's abrupt slowing on its axis should have produced a global catastrophe leading, perhaps, to the destruction of all life. However, nothing but minor tidal disturbances have been observed so far\"''.<ref>[[Robert Silverberg]], \"Thomas the Proclaimer\", Ch.1</ref>\n\nFor his part, the Portuguese [[Jos\u00e9 Saramago]] apparently refers to the Wells story in his novel ''[[Cain (novel)| Cain]]'', an irreverent retelling of the [[Bible]], when retelling the episode of God \"stopping the sun\" in the [[Book of Joshua]] (to which the pastor in the Wells story also refers). The very flawed God depicted by Saramago was unable to stop the disastrous effects of stopping the movement of the Easth - so he did not do so, performing just a much simpler and limited miracle which still did the job.\n\n==References==\n{{commonscat}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikisource|The Man Who Could Work Miracles|The Man Who Could Work Miracles}}\n* \"[http://www.gutenberg.org/files/27365/27365-h/27365-h.htm#Page_325 The Man Who Could Work Miracles]\" at [[Project Gutenberg]]\n* [http://ebooks.adelaide.edu.au/w/wells/hg/w45cb/chapter21.html ''The Man Who Could Work Miracles'':] short story by H. G. Wells\n* {{librivox book | title=The Man who could Work Miracles | author=H. G. Wells}}