{"title_page": "List of films about the Rwandan genocide", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Rwandan genocide}}\nThis is a '''[[filmography]]''' for [[films]] and artistry on the graphic, theatrical and conventional, documental portrayal of the 1994 '''[[Rwandan genocide]]'''. In 2005 [[Alison Des Forges]] wrote that eleven years after the genocide films for popular audiences on the subject  greatly increased \"widespread realization of the horror that had taken the lives of more than half a million Tutsi\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.idrc.ca/rwandagenocide/ev-108178-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210180655/http://www.idrc.ca/rwandagenocide/ev-108178-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html |archivedate=2010-02-10 }}</ref>\n \n\n* ''[[Hotel Rwanda]]'' (2004). Dramatic feature film about [[Paul Rusesabagina]], a Kigali hotelier, and the events around the [[H\u00f4tel des Mille Collines]], a sanctuary for Tutsis and moderate Hutus after its owner shut his doors against the genocide. The film was nominated for multiple Academy Awards, is on the [[American Film Institute]]'s list of the 100 most inspirational films of all time, and appears on the [[IMDb]]'s Top 250 highest rated movies of all time.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/chart/top?ref_=nv_mv_250_6</ref>\n* ''[[Shooting Dogs]]'' (called ''Beyond the Gates'' in the US) (2005).  A priest ([[John Hurt]]) and a teacher ([[Hugh Dancy]]) get caught up in the Rwandan genocide of 1994. Dramatic feature film directed by [[Michael Caton-Jones]].\n* ''[[Sometimes in April]]'' (2005).  Dramatic feature film detailing events prior, during and after the genocide through the story of an intermarried Hutu-Tutsi family.\n* ''[[A Sunday in Kigali]]'' (2006). Dramatic feature film based on the book \n* ''[[Shake Hands with the Devil (2007 film)|Shake Hands with the Devil]]'' (2007).  Dramatic feature film based on the Lieutenant-General [[Rom\u00e9o Dallaire]]'s  book ''[[Shake Hands with the Devil (book)|Shake Hands with the Devil: The Failure of Humanity in Rwanda]]'' (''J'ai serr\u00e9 la main du diable: La faillite de l'humanit\u00e9 au Rwanda'') (2003).\n*''[[Munyurangabo]]'' (2007). An orphan of the Rwandan genocide travels from Kigali to the countryside on a quest for justice (from IMDb). Directed by [[Lee Isaac Chung]]. Production: Almond Tree Films. Official Selection- Un Certain Regard, Cannes. Grand Jury Prize, AFI.<ref>Munyurangabo review, Roger Ebert- http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090722/REVIEWS/907229989</ref>\n* ''The Day God Walked Away'' (2009)\n* ''[[Kinyarwanda (film)|Kinyarwanda]]'' (2011). Dramatic feature that tells the story of hope, redemption and religious tolerance in the midst of the 1994 Rwandan genocide. It premiered at the [[27th Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2011 where it won the World Cinema Dramatic Audience Award.<ref>Kinyarwanda, the movie. Interwoven tales from the Rwandan genocide - [http://www.thisisafrica.me/photography-film/detail/1255/Kinyarwanda,-the-movie.-Interwoven-tales-from-the-Rwandan-genocide Thisisafrica]</ref><ref>[http://www.indiewire.com/article/meet_the_2011_sundance_filmmakers_kinyarwanda_director_alrick_brown/# indieWIRE January 20, 2011]</ref>\n* ''[[94 Terror (film)|94 Terror]]'' (2018)  Keza survived the Tutsi and Hutu slaughter in the 1994 Rwanda genocide and recounts the tragedy and her escape from Rwanda to Uganda through the Kagera River.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rwandan Genocide movie set to premiere in Kampala |url=https://bigeye.ug/rwandan-genocide-movie-set-to-premiere-in-kampala/ |accessdate=26 March 2019 |agency=Bigeye}}</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\n\n*''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm Journey into Darkness]'' (1994). Documentary film shot within Rwanda throughout the genocide, by the journalist [[Fergal Keane]]. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]] production.\n*''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm A Culture of Murder]'' (1994). Documentary film on the Rwandan genocide, and the plight of its refugees, by the journalist [[Steve Bradshaw]]. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]] production.\n* ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm The Bloody Tricolor]'' (1995). Documentary film on the involvement of France in Rwanda prior to the genocide. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]] production.\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20070102224805/http://www.documen.tv/asset/Rwanda_film.html  ''Rwanda, how history can lead to genocide''] (1995). Directed by Robert Genoud.\n* ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm Valentina's Story]'' (1997). Documentary film on the story of Valentina, a survivor of the Rwandan genocide, by the journalist [[Fergal Keane]]. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]] production.\n* ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm When Good Men Do Nothing]'' (1997). Documentary film on the failure of the [[United Nations|UN]], and the west, by the journalist [[Steve Bradshaw]]. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]] production.\n* ''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm Triumph of Evil]'' (1998). Documentary film on the failure of the [[United Nations|UN]], and the west, an adaption, originally by the journalist [[Steve Bradshaw]]. A [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]] [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/Frontline] production.\n*''[[L'Afrique en morceaux]]'' (2000). Documentary film directed by [[Jihan El-Tahri]] <ref name=\"olivier\">{{cite news |url=http://www.afrik.com/article2267.html | title=L\u2019Afrique en morceaux : une le\u00e7on d\u2019histoire imm\u00e9diate | work=Afrik |date=23 February 2001 | accessdate=March 10, 2012 | author=Zegna-Rata, Olivier | language=French}}</ref>\n* ''[[Umurage]]'' (2002). Documentary film directed by Gorka Gamarra about the process of reconciliation between victims and perpetrators in Rwanda.\n* ''[[Shake Hands with the Devil: The Journey of Rom\u00e9o Dallaire]]'' (2004). Documentary film directed by [[Peter Raymont]]. [[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]].\n* ''Keepers of Memory'' (2004). Documentary film directed by the journalist [[Eric Kabera]].\n* Beyond the Gates (2005)\n* ''[https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/ghosts/video/ Ghosts of Rwanda] ''(2005). Documentary film directed by the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]. Post by the [https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/pages/frontline/shows/evil/ Frontline: The Triumph of Evil] website.\n* [https://www.pbs.org/newshour/bb/africa/jan-june06/darfur_4-12.html ''Exploring Rwanda and Darfur''] (2006). TV Documentary directed by the [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS]]. Post by ''[[The NewsHour with Jim Lehrer]]'', on the website.\n*[[Screamers (2006 film)|''Screamers'']] (2006). Documentary by director Carla Garapedian. The documentary examines the repeating pattern of genocide, from the Armenian genocide, to the Holocaust, Cambodia, Bosnia, Rwanda, up to Darfur today. After its theatrical release in the US and Canada, the documentary was screened in the U.S. Congress, British Parliament and European Parliament to raise awareness about [[genocide education]].<ref name=screamersmovei>\"Screamers movie official\" http://www.screamersmovie.com/press.html</ref><ref name=imdb>\"Screamers(2006)\" https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0823668/</ref> The full documentary can be watched from the official YouTube channel of the movie [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=EpHkzwE4qzg].\n* [http://www.floresderuanda.com/ruanda/rwanda-genocide-film.html ''Flowers of Rwanda''] (2008). Documentary film directed by [[David Mu\u00f1oz (director)|David Mu\u00f1oz]]. Post by the Hibrida Newsgroup, on the website.\n* ''[http://mediastorm.org/0024.htm Intended Consequences]'' (2008). By [[Jonathan Torgovnik]] on [http://mediastorm.org MediaStorm]\n* [http://www.gacacafilms.com ''Gacaca Film Series''] (2002\u20132009) Official site for the documentary film series that includes \"My Neighbor My Killer\" (Official Selection at Cannes Film Festival), \"Gacaca Living Together in Rwanda?,\" \"In Rwanda We Say...The family that does not speak dies\" and \"The Notebooks of Memory\" By Emmy-winner Anne Aghion\n* ''[[Flower in the Gun Barrel]]'' (2009). Documentary that focuses on the process of reconciliation and forgiveness in post genocide Rwanda.\n* [http://www.agenerationaftergenocide.com ''A Generation After Genocide''] (2010). Documentary film that follows three orphaned youth of different class, gender and ethnicity who are all connected by soccer. A Family-Style Films production. Currently in production. Directed by Torey Kohara and Jonathan Weiman.\n* ''[[Burden of My Heart]]'' (2011). A poetic documentary film about the lives of the survivors and the ways of remembering in Rwanda 16 years after the genocide. A Finnish-Rwandan co-production. Awarded at Tampere film festival and DokLeipzig. Directed by Iris Olsson & Yves Niyongabo\n* [[Duhozanye|Duhozanye: A Rwandan Village of Widows]] (2011). By [[Karoline Frogner]]\n* ''[[If Only We Had Listened]]'' (2011). Director: Sean Bloomfield\n* ''[[The 600: A Soldiers' Story]]'' (2019). Documentary film on the little known story of a surrounded battalion that started the counterattack to end the Rwandan Genocide against the Tutsi in 1994, by producer [[Richard Hall (producer)|Richard Hall]]. A [[Great Blue Productions]] film.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}<!--added above categories/infobox footers by script-assisted edit-->\n\n[[Category:Lists of films by topic|Rwandan genocide]]\n[[Category:Works about the Rwandan genocide| ]]\n[[Category:Rwanda history-related lists|Films, Genocide]]\n[[Category:Crime-related lists|Rwandan genocide]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{Rwandan genocide}}\nThis is a '''[[filmography]]''' for [[films]] and artistry on the graphic, theatrical and conventional, documental portrayal of the 1994 '''[[Rwandan genocide]]'''. In 2005 [[Alison Des Forges]] wrote that eleven years after the genocide films for popular audiences on the subject  greatly increased \"widespread realization of the horror that had taken the lives of more than half a million Tutsi\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.idrc.ca/rwandagenocide/ev-108178-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2010-08-30 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100210180655/http://www.idrc.ca/rwandagenocide/ev-108178-201-1-DO_TOPIC.html |archivedate=2010-02-10 }}</ref>\n \n* ''[[94 Terror (film)|94 Terror]]'' (2018)  Keza survived the Tutsi and Hutu slaughter in the 1994 Rwanda genocide and recounts the tragedy and her escape from Rwanda to Uganda through the Kagera River.<ref>{{cite news |title=Rwandan Genocide movie set to premiere in Kampala |url=https://bigeye.ug/rwandan-genocide-movie-set-to-premiere-in-kampala/ |accessdate=26 March 2019 |agency=Bigeye}}</ref>\n\n* ''[[Hotel Rwanda]]'' (2004). Dramatic feature film about [[Paul Rusesabagina]], a Kigali hotelier, and the events around the [[H\u00f4tel des Mille Collines]], a sanctuary for Tutsis and moderate Hutus after its owner shut his doors against the genocide. The film was nominated for multiple Academy Awards, is on the [[American Film Institute]]'s list of the 100 most inspirational films of all time, and appears on the [[IMDb]]'s Top 250 highest rated movies of all time.<ref>https://www.imdb.com/chart/top?ref_=nv_mv_250_6</ref>\n* ''[[Shooting Dogs]]'' (called ''Beyond the Gates'' in the US) (2005).  A priest ([[John Hurt]]) and a teacher ([[Hugh Dancy]]) get caught up in the Rwandan genocide of 1994. Dramatic feature film directed by [[Michael Caton-Jones]].\n* ''[[Sometimes in April]]'' (2005).  Dramatic feature film detailing events prior, during and after the genocide through the story of an intermarried Hutu-Tutsi family.\n* ''[[A Sunday in Kigali]]'' (2006). Dramatic feature film based on the book \n* ''[[Shake Hands with the Devil (2007 film)|Shake Hands with the Devil]]'' (2007).  Dramatic feature film based on the Lieutenant-General [[Rom\u00e9o Dallaire]]'s  book ''[[Shake Hands with the Devil (book)|Shake Hands with the Devil: The Failure of Humanity in Rwanda]]'' (''J'ai serr\u00e9 la main du diable: La faillite de l'humanit\u00e9 au Rwanda'') (2003).\n*''[[Munyurangabo]]'' (2007). An orphan of the Rwandan genocide travels from Kigali to the countryside on a quest for justice (from IMDb). Directed by [[Lee Isaac Chung]]. Production: Almond Tree Films. Official Selection- Un Certain Regard, Cannes. Grand Jury Prize, AFI.<ref>Munyurangabo review, Roger Ebert- http://rogerebert.suntimes.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090722/REVIEWS/907229989</ref>\n* ''The Day God Walked Away'' (2009)\n* ''[[Kinyarwanda (film)|Kinyarwanda]]'' (2011). Dramatic feature that tells the story of hope, redemption and religious tolerance in the midst of the 1994 Rwandan genocide. It premiered at the [[27th Sundance Film Festival]] in January 2011 where it won the World Cinema Dramatic Audience Award.<ref>Kinyarwanda, the movie. Interwoven tales from the Rwandan genocide - [http://www.thisisafrica.me/photography-film/detail/1255/Kinyarwanda,-the-movie.-Interwoven-tales-from-the-Rwandan-genocide Thisisafrica]</ref><ref>[http://www.indiewire.com/article/meet_the_2011_sundance_filmmakers_kinyarwanda_director_alrick_brown/# indieWIRE January 20, 2011]</ref>\n\n==Documentaries==\n\n*''[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/programmes/panorama/3585473.stm Journey into Darkness]'' (1994). Documentary film shot within Rwanda throughout the genocide, by the journalist [[Fergal Keane]]. A [[British Broadcasting Corporation|BBC]] [[Panorama (TV series)|Panorama]] production.\n*''[http://news.bbc